{
  "doc_id": "55381",
  "text": "The increased PO 4 -P export after clear-cutting in C34 was probably due to increased runoff because there was no increase in PO 4 -P concentrations. Phosphate could originate from logging residues, which released phosphorus rapidly [CITATION_1] , and decomposing understory vegetation after soil preparation [CITATION_2] . Elevated ground water levels and more superficial water flow paths after clear-cutting may also have promoted PO 4 -P solubility and transport to the stream [CITATION_3] . However, the export of PO 4 -P did not increase in the C11 catchment even though the ground water levels were higher in catchment C11 than in catchment C34 . The longer average distance to the stream and presence of peat with high P retention capacity in the buffer zone [CITATION_4] could explain the differences in the behaviour between catchments C11 and C34. The increase in the PO 4 -P export in the first year after clear-cutting in the C8 catchment is probably due to unusually low PO 4 -P loads in the reference catchment in that year (data not shown) rather than treatment effect.",
